{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context / Why\n\nAll code landing on `main` goes through Gerrit's two-vote gate (LLM-Review + Verified).\nWe want every such commit associated with a rebar ticket, enforced as part of the\n**Verified (CI)** leg — the only enforcement point that both blocks submit AND can resolve\nan ID against the live store. A `rebar-ticket:` commit trailer is introduced by this work as\nthe convention (no code parses one yet, so the first submitted commits must carry it). CI does\nnot apply to specialized branches (the `tickets` branch never goes through Gerrit), so this\ngates only code changes to `main`. The mechanism is intended to be reusable, so it is documented as a\nfirst-class rebar convention.\n\n## What\n\nAdd a `rebar verify-commit-ticket` check that extracts a ticket reference from a commit\nmessage and resolves it against the authoritative store via the standard config store logic\n(`config.tracker_dir()` / `config.tickets_branch()`), then wire it as a fail-fast job in\n`gerrit-verify.yaml` so a missing/unresolvable ticket drives Verified-1. Accept alias, full\nID, short ID, and Jira key (project prefix) — all handled by the existing `resolve_ticket_id`.\n\n## Decisions\n\n- **Location:** canonical is the `rebar-ticket: <id>` trailer; a leading `<id>:` subject token\n  is also accepted. First-element-ONLY enforcement is NOT adopted: no performance gain (a\n  single store lookup regardless of position) and no fragility gain (both are fixed-position\n  parses), while it would constrain every subject and eat the 50-char budget.\n- **Single source of truth:** the expected-format wording lives in ONE Python constant\n  (`EXPECTED_FORMAT`). The CLI error and `--help` print it; the golden help capture and a\n  doc-drift test pin `docs/commit-ticket-trailer.md` to it, so they cannot diverge.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] New `src/rebar/_commands/verify_commit.py`:\n      - `EXPECTED_FORMAT: str` — the shared expected-format/accepted-forms/example/fix text.\n      - `extract_ticket_refs(message) -> list[str]` — pull candidates from the `rebar-ticket:`\n        trailer (case-insensitive; value tokens split on whitespace and stripped of `()`,`,`)\n        and from a leading `<id>:` subject token. **SECURITY:** drop any candidate that is not a\n        single safe token — reject anything with `/`, `\\`, `..`, whitespace, or control chars\n        (require `^[A-Za-z0-9][A-Za-z0-9._-]{0,127}$`) BEFORE any store lookup, so a crafted\n        `rebar-ticket: ../../etc/passwd` can never reach the resolver's `os.path.isdir(tracker/\n        <cand>)` fast path. Shape-matching (full/short/alias/Jira/prefix) stays in\n        `resolve_ticket_id`; do NOT duplicate its `_FULL_ID_RE`/`_SHORT_ID_RE`/`_JIRA_KEY_RE`\n        (avoids drift — a plausible-but-wrong inline shape would silently diverge).\n      - `verify_commit_message(message, *, root=None) -> (ok: bool, tried: list[str], detail)` —\n        resolve each safe candidate via `resolve_ticket_id` against `config.tracker_dir(root)`;\n        ok if ANY resolves.\n- [ ] CLI `rebar verify-commit-ticket` (intercept in `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py`, mirroring\n      the `review-plan` intercept). Input is ONE of `--rev <ref>` (reads via\n      `git show -s --format=%B`), `--message-file <p>`, or `--message <s>` (mutually exclusive;\n      default `--rev HEAD`). Behavior:\n      - `verify.require_ticket_for_commit` false → exit 0 (no-op / staged rollout).\n      - Merge commit (>1 parent, when `--rev` given) → exit 0 (exempt).\n      - A safe candidate resolves → exit 0.\n      - Else exit 1, printing `EXPECTED_FORMAT`: the `rebar-ticket: <id>` trailer format, the\n        leading `<id>:` alternative, the accepted ID forms (alias/full/short/Jira `<PREFIX>-<n>`),\n        a worked example, the candidate(s) tried (or `(none present)`) with \"none resolved\", and\n        the fix (add the trailer, `git commit --amend`, re-push).\n      - I/O robustness: a bad `--rev` / missing `--message-file` / unreadable-or-absent store\n        exits non-zero with a DISTINGUISHABLE error naming the cause (git failure, missing file,\n        store not found) — never conflated with the missing-ticket diagnostic (so CI infra errors\n        are told apart from a genuine ticket-less commit).\n- [ ] Registration = PURE INTERCEPT (matching `review-plan` / `verify-completion`): the arm in\n      `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` `main()` fires before `_dispatch` and owns its OWN argparse\n      `--help` (which prints usage + `EXPECTED_FORMAT`). Intercepts carry NO `help/<sub>.txt`, NO\n      `overview.txt` line, NO `tests/golden/cli_help/` files, and are NOT in the coverage test's\n      `individual` set — they are invisible to the pinned-help parity contract\n      (`test_routable_set_matches_pinned_help_set`), so none of those touchpoints apply.\n      (Verified: review-plan/verify-completion/workflow follow exactly this pattern.)\n- [ ] Config: `verify.require_ticket_for_commit: bool = False` in `VerifyConfig` +\n      `_SECTIONS['verify']` in `src/rebar/config.py` (env\n      `REBAR_VERIFY_REQUIRE_TICKET_FOR_COMMIT` via the generic env layer); enabled for THIS\n      project in `rebar.toml`.\n- [ ] Store resolution uses the standard config helpers `config.tracker_dir()` /\n      `config.tickets_branch()` and is overridable via `REBAR_TRACKER_DIR` (relocates the store,\n      highest precedence) / `tracker.dir` / `tracker.branch` — no bespoke store path. (Local\n      resolution reads the mounted store files; the CI job separately mounts that store — see\n      below.)\n- [ ] CI: `.github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml` gains a `require-ticket` job (needs\n      `clear-vote`; `build-and-test` + `vote` gain it in `needs` so a failure fails the run →\n      Verified-1, fail-fast before the matrix). Runners are GitHub-hosted + ephemeral (fresh\n      workspace per run); fetch+worktree is used (over per-file `git show tickets:path`) because\n      the standard resolver needs a real tracker dir to read. Steps:\n      - checkout the Gerrit change (`checkout-gerrit-change-action`) + `pip install -e .`;\n      - mount the authoritative tickets store from GitHub, **idempotently and with retry**:\n        `git worktree prune` + `rm -rf .tickets-tracker` first; then up to 3 attempts of\n        `timeout 60 git fetch --depth=1 https://github.com/${{ github.repository }}\n        '+tickets:refs/remotes/gh-tickets'` (short sleep-backoff between attempts); then\n        `git worktree add --detach .tickets-tracker gh-tickets`. On persistent fetch failure,\n        print a DISTINGUISHABLE infra-error (not a missing-ticket error) advising `recheck`, and\n        fail closed (two-vote fail-closed model);\n      - `export REBAR_TRACKER_DIR=\"$PWD/.tickets-tracker\"` (pin the store explicitly rather than\n        rely on the default name) and run `rebar verify-commit-ticket --rev HEAD` (the CLI reads\n        the message itself from git; no untrusted commit text is interpolated onto a command line).\n- [ ] Tests `tests/unit/test_verify_commit_ticket.py`:\n      - extraction: trailer with parenthetical, leading `<id>:`, multiple, none, AND a\n        path-traversal candidate is dropped (security);\n      - resolution against a fixture store for full / short / alias / prefix, and a Jira key via\n        a `.bridge_state/bindings.json` fixture;\n      - config-gate off → exit 0; enabled + no ticket → exit 1 AND the diagnostic contains the\n        trailer format + accepted forms + an example (asserted against `EXPECTED_FORMAT`);\n      - merge-commit exempt; the three input modes; a valid leading-`<id>:` commit → exit 0.\n- [ ] Doc-drift test: a unit test imports `EXPECTED_FORMAT` and asserts\n      `docs/commit-ticket-trailer.md` contains its text, so docs cannot silently drift.\n- [ ] Docs (accurate + discoverable; a reusable, rebar-enforced convention for BOTH clients and\n      contributors):\n      - `CONTRIBUTING.md` — every commit to `main` must carry a resolvable ticket ref; the\n        trailer format, the leading-`<id>:` alternative, accepted ID forms, CI enforcement.\n      - `CLAUDE.md` — in the `## Git workflow (code changes)` section, the same for agents.\n      - `docs/config.md` — the `verify.require_ticket_for_commit` flag.\n      - `docs/commit-ticket-trailer.md` (new) — the reusable mechanism: trailer convention +\n        `rebar verify-commit-ticket` + extraction/resolution + config; linked from the two above.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `pytest tests/unit/test_verify_commit_ticket.py -q`\n- `pytest tests/interfaces/contracts/test_help_overview_coverage.py -q` (intercept leaves parity intact)\n- `rebar verify-commit-ticket --message \"x: no ticket\"; echo $?` → 1, printing EXPECTED_FORMAT\n- `rebar verify-commit-ticket --message-file <(git show -s --format=%B HEAD); echo $?` → 0\n- `grep -l 'rebar-ticket:' CONTRIBUTING.md CLAUDE.md docs/config.md docs/commit-ticket-trailer.md`\n  (all four document the trailer)\n- CI-path (`require-ticket` job) is proved by an operator throwaway change, like the two-vote E2E.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Non-Gerrit paths (the `tickets` branch; direct GitHub pushes — already blocked by the ruleset).\n- An advisory client-side `commit-msg` hook (optional future nicety).\n- A `rebar-ticket: none` bypass sentinel (kept strict; merge commits are the only exemption)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783047710771894001,"uuid":"7e767aff-494b-4574-a99a-5d58e906034c"}